passages.text: Oh Behave! Earnings in Late August?!

Both Credit and Equities gained on the week, with Equities outperforming: The SPX returned \(+2.8\%\) driven by upward GDP revisions, dovish signals from the Fed and outperformance by major tech and select earnings surprises. Treasuries continued to rally this week on the back of expectations of a rate cut at the September meeting, with the 5yr - 5bps to \(3.60\%\) and 10yr - 3bps to \(4.23\%\) . As of Thursday's close, JULI returned \(+0.7\%\) , with HG Retail in line. JPHY returned \(+0.8\%\) , with HY Retail outperforming at \(+0.96\%\) . Gains were fairly consistent across ratings, with the lowest quality outperforming: As \(+0.7\%\) , BBBs \(+0.7\%\) , BBs \(+0.76\%\) BS \(+0.89\%\) and CCCs \(+1.44\%\) .

Retail was well bid in late August in HY on the back of better- than- expected earnings from KSS, VSCO and WOOF.BBWI, BBY and DKS were in line/ mixed and FL & GAP missed. Tariffs remain a hot topic, with Trump threatening more furniture tariffs and retailers starting to add them into their guide. This week, KSS eliminated the upper end of its GPM guide owing to tariffs (now \(+30\) bps vs \(+30 - 50\) bps), BBWI (which was expected to be more immune, but has some Canadian exposure) sees \(\) 85\(mn of impact and GAP\) \ \(150 - 175\) mn this year. From last week, WMT will keep prices low as long as they can (pressuring everyone else), but will have to take some pricing for tariffs. See Tables 4- 6, below, for the full calendar; earnings recap and takeaways, and equity takes linked.

We recommend buying Macy's (M) \(4.500\%\) '34s at \(7\%\) YTW, going into earnings next week (9/3). We believe M is a share gainer in a volatile consumer and department store environment and as evidenced by this week's retail earnings, the consumer continues to respond well to promotion, but also looking for newness. We expect M to offset the potential tariff headwinds through selective pricing increases. We prefer being long- risk more diversified department stores and like the spread and yield pickup for the name compared with its higher- levered peers.

Kohl's (KSS) - We updated our forecast after a solid 2Q, and clarified confusing negative press in our note When Life Gets Real, Start Here - with the company numbers and note the press. Bonds were up 4pts on the day (2pts of that was retracing pressure from Tuesday on negative press - details below). We would stay Neutral KSS after this week's dip and rebound. The secured notes are back to \(10\%\) . We also updated our forecast, for which we largely maintained our FY25 estimates

- Kohl's (KSS) was in the press again, in what we call an inflammatory story, on Tuesday. Bloomberg reported that KSS is asking some vendors for more time to settle invoices. The story stems from a March letter the company sent to suppliers about "standardizing... payment terms in line with the retail industry at large." This week's earnings showed no material change in payment terms for 2Q (May-Jul), as days payable declined from 49 days last year to 44 days this year (we believe the decline may be related to tariffs, as tariff payments increase inventory balances, but the payment is made upfront, not on typical payable terms). During FY24, KSS paid vendors more quickly than Macy's - days varied from 39 to 70 vs M's at 49-87, and JWN's at 54-76.

- Dick's (DKS) / Foot Locker (FL) deal to close Sept 8, after the HSR waiting period expired this week. Existing FL shareholders are voting between either taking the \(24 in cash or receiving 0.1168 shares of DKS for each share of FL stock they own. This is the final requirement from a regulatory approval standpoint. The deal is now slated to close September 8th. DKS extended the exchange offer for the FL 4% senior notes due '29 (to be exchanged into DKS notes) to September 9th from August 29th. Foot Locker reported weak earnings, with SSS -2% (vs street +0.1%), GPM 27.4% vs 28.7% est (-50bps Y/Y) and EBITDA of \$35mn vs \$66mn est. DKS reported in-line earnings, with SSS +5% (vs Street +3.1%), GPM 37.1% vs 37.0% est and EBITDA of \$558mn vs \$557mn est.

- Saks Global (SAGLEN, SGUSLL) related S546mn CMBS secured an extension to finalize refinancing, but not details yet on the refi. Bloomberg reported that the loan was transferred to a workout specialist and given a 60-day extension. This is the 2-part CMBS loan from 2015 financing by HBS Global Properties, a real estate entity formed by Hudson's Bay and Simon Property that held 42 Saks & Lord & Taylor properties (20 owned locations and 22 ground leased, initially valued at \$2.1bn).

- The Walgreens Boots Alliance (WBA) acquisition by Sycamore officially closed this week. Under Sycamore's private ownership, Walgreens, The Boots Group, Shields Health Solutions, CareCentrix and VillageMD will all be standalone companies. It also announced that Mike Motz, former CEO of Staples US retail (another Sycamore-owned company), will be replacing Tim Wentworth as CEO of Walgreens. Wentworth will continue to serve as an ongoing director.
